        <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a> â€º </div>                  <h2 class="title">Football Scouting Services Information</h2>
                                
        
        <div id="content-area">
          <div id="node-331" class="node node-type-record-request build-mode-full clearfix">
  
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <span class="submitted">
          Submitted by Anonymous on Fri, 2011-11-18 14:21        </span>
      
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <div class="field field-type-text field-field-requester">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                      <div class="field-label-inline-first">
              Requester:&nbsp;</div>
                    Prince, Seth        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="field field-type-text field-field-organization">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                      <div class="field-label-inline-first">
              Organization:&nbsp;</div>
                    The Oregonian        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="field field-type-date field-field-initial-date">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                      <div class="field-label-inline-first">
              Initial Request Date:&nbsp;</div>
                    <span class="date-display-single">03/07/2011</span>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<div class="field field-type-date field-field-completion-date">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                      <div class="field-label-inline-first">
              Request Completion Date:&nbsp;</div>
                    <span class="date-display-single">06/20/2011</span>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<p>I&rsquo;m writing to request the following information related to the NCAA investigation into Oregon&rsquo;s use of scouting services:<br />
1. From late 2009 or early 2010: Documents in which UO requests a W9 form Elite Scouting Services LLC in Hollywood, Fla.<br />
2. From July 26, 2010: Copy of letter sent certified mail from law firm of Frank - Wienberg - Black to UO (attn: Chip Kelly) on behalf of Charles Fishbein of Elite Scouting Services. Letter advises university that Willie Lyles had been terminated as an employee in January 2010 prior to UO paying $25,000 to a &quot;Willie Lyles/Elite Scouting?. Also seek all subsequent related correspondence.<br />
3. Any other invoices, checks or other payment/cashing information as well as tax documents ? dating to 2006 - between UO and the following:<br />
a) Willie J Lyles<br />
b) Elite Scouting Services<br />
c) Complete Scouting Services<br />
d) Baron Flenory<br />
e) New Level Athletics.<br />
4. All e-mails between UO compliance office between or among the following - Chip Kelly; athletic directors Pat Kilkenny, Mike Bellotti, Rob Mullens - related to Elite Scouting Services and/or Willie Lyles and/or Lyles' Complete Scouting Services.<br />
5. Any travel expenses incurred by Willie J Lyles paid by UO, including any related to the recruiting visits of [named students]. Also any travel expenses by Lyles incurred as [named student's] guest in December 2010 at the Home Depot College Football Awards program in Orlando, Fla., and any other related postseason award travels.<br />
6. Any itinerary information related to the recruiting visits of [named students].<br />
7. All cell phone records from coach Chip Kelly to Houston area codes - 281, 713 and 832 - since his hire in spring 2007. And anything specifically to the following numbers: 832-647-7586; 713?748?8331; 713?941?2773; 832?647?7586.<br />
8. All cell phone records from assistant coach Gary Campbell to Houston area codes - 281, 713 and 832 - since spring 2007. And anything specifically to the following numbers: 832-647-7586; 713?748?8331; 713?941?2773; 832?647?7586.<br />
9. A record of all correspondence with the NCAA related to Willie J Lyles involvement with UO.<br />
10. A record of all media requests related to Willie J Lyles, scouting services, Baron Flenory and the NCAA investigation.</p>
  </div>

